3_1	0.19407623	The seed of the idea that would become the Library of Congress lay in the fact that while there were sufficient libraries in Philadelphia, where the U.S. government had resided for a decade, there were none in Washington, where the government would soon be.
3_2	0.10111394	That the library would grow into a pre-eminent world institution was beyond imagination.
3_3	0.10628193	On April 24, 1800, President John Adams approved an appropriation of $5,000 to purchase ''such books as may be necessary for the use of Congress''.
3_4	0.092005346	Books, mostly on history, economics and law, were ordered from London.
3_5	0.09700963	They arrived in 1801 and were shelved in the new U.S.
3_6	0.0979982	Capitol. The collection consisted of just 740 volumes and three maps.
3_7	0.20987948	Next Monday, millions of books and much history later, the Library of Congress celebrates its 200th anniversary as an institution that grew, in the words of one of its biographers, into ''a symbol of American democracy and faith in the power of learning''.
3_8	0.11392463	The celebration includes a major exhibition, ''Thomas Jefferson,'' featuring the first-ever reassembly of Jefferson's 1815 library in one place, arranged by the system he devised.
