9_24	0.10407762	In doing so, Hutson was performing excavation on a document that is a touchstone of American history.
9_25	0.093947817	The ``wall of separation'' metaphor, though not found in the Constitution, is often invoked as shorthand for the religion clause of the First Amendment to the Constitution, which says that ``Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereof''.
9_26	0.10148819	The import of the ``separation'' language has been argued over by scholars and cited in at least 50 Supreme Court cases dealing with the relationship between government and religion.
9_27	0.097945366	The Supreme Court declared in Reynolds vs.
9_28	0.13438919	United States in 1878 that the ``wall'' metaphor was ``almost an authoritative declaration of the scope and effect'' of the First Amendment.
9_29	0.061930305	Since then, justices like Potter Stewart and William Rehnquist have argued that Jefferson's words were misused.
9_30	0.052490132	The FBI discovered that Jefferson had crossed out the word ``eternal'' preceding ``separation of Church and State'' _ as some scholars had correctly guessed years before _ and inked over ``the duties of my station, which are merely temporal''.
9_31	0.097163285	That last word meant secular, as opposed to spiritual.
9_32	0.069863089	In his essay, Hutson surmised that Jefferson removed these phrases because they might sound ``too anti-religious to pious New England ears''.
